02531nam a22005175i 9780824845049DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20221993hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780824845049  a(DE-B1597)626909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSCI1000002bisacsh1 aValier, Kathy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFerns of Hawai`i /cKathy Valier. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©1993  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA fern-lover once wrote: “If you wish to know ferns you must follow them.” Hawaiʻi, with approximately two hundred species of ferns and fern allies, is the ideal place to begin the journey, and Ferns of Hawaiʻi the ideal guide. Written for those who wish to become followers of these delightfully subtle plants, this introductory work begins with a description of Hawaiʻi’s ferns and their ecology. Sections on where to find ferns, their use by Hawaiians, and common, Hawaiian, and scientific names are provided. With the aid of color and black and white photographs, naturalist Kathy Valier describes more than sixty of the most common ferns growing wild in Hawaiʻi, from the tiny water fern azolla to the wiry masses of the scrambling uluhe. Information on habitat and distribution accompanies each description.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aSCIENCE / Natural History.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824845049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824845049/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  a